<h3 id="how-much-does-it-pay">How Much Does it Pay?</h3>
<p>Most freelance writers have a tough time making much money, but technical writing is among the highest-paid segments of the industry. Iâ€™ve been paid anywhere between $200 and $700 per article depending on the topic, publication, and length. It usually works out to between $50 and $250 per hour (excluding administrative work and pitching). Obviously, thatâ€™s a big spread, so youâ€™ll have to balance the kind of writing you want to do with your desire for income.</p>

<p>For example, you might get paid $500 for a long piece about something youâ€™ve never used before. The upside to this kind of post is that <em>youâ€™ll learn a lot</em>, but the downside is that your hourly rate isnâ€™t great if it takes you 20 hours of work.</p>

<h3 id="what-skills-do-you-need-to-have">What Skills Do You Need to Have?</h3>
<p>Technical bloggers are well-paid because they have to have specialized knowledge that can take years to acquire. Writing in-depth software engineering tutorials can require quite a bit of research - even if you are already familiar with the topic. Iâ€™ve been writing software for almost ten years now, and some articles take me 2-3 hours of research before I can even get started writing.</p>

<p>If youâ€™re a new software developer or <a href="/posts/advice-for-new-bootcamp-graduates">recent bootcamp graduate</a>, you might have to start with introductory blog posts on the lower end of the pay scale. Once you get good at finding niches to pitch articles about, you are essentially getting paid to learn new things. Itâ€™s not a bad deal.</p>

<p>Iâ€™ve found that certain topics do tend to pay a little better than others, but as you might expect, theyâ€™re the ones that take longer to learn. For example, DevOps is a hot topic right now, but learning Docker, Kubernetes, Serverless, and all the tools involved in those technologies is quite an undertaking.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s also helpful to write for companies whose products youâ€™re familiar with. For example, one of the first blogs to reach out to me was <a href="https://codeship.com/">Codeshipâ€™s</a> because we were using them at The Graide Network and my previous startup.</p>

