<h4 id="4-start-increasing-your-rate">4. Start increasing your rate</h4>
<p>Increasing your pay rate doesnâ€™t just mean writing for publications that pay the most per post. Some posts are much easier to write than others.</p>

<p>So, I track the number of hours it takes me to create each post, the amount I get paid, and how much I enjoy writing that kind of post. Iâ€™m trying to do more of the work I enjoy and less of the work I donâ€™t while maximizing my effective hourly rate.</p>

<p>Also, a publicationâ€™s posted rate is rarely the highest rate theyâ€™ll pay writers. Most offer a low rate to new writers but will increase your rate if you ask for it, and youâ€™ve proven yourself to be reliable.</p>

<h4 id="5-find-ways-to-decrease-your-research-time">5. Find ways to decrease your research time</h4>
<p>Try to double-down on topics you know so you can decrease your research time per post. For example, if you are writing a post about setting up a Laravel application, keep the app on your local machine for a future article about something related.</p>

<p>You can also pitch similar topics to different publications, but donâ€™t reuse the same blog post. Your clients will not like that and itâ€™s dishonest.</p>

<h4 id="6-the-pay-lag">6. The pay lag</h4>
<p>Finally, be aware that freelance writing isnâ€™t necessarily quick money. Most publications pay you 30-60 days after you invoice them, but some pay <em>after</em> your post is published, which can be weeks or months later.</p>

<p>If you need money faster, you might be able to negotiate better payment terms with smaller clients, but big companies have established processes and may not bend them easily.</p>

<h3 id="should-you-start-freelance-technical-blogging">Should You Start Freelance Technical Blogging?</h3>
<p>It depends.</p>

<p>First, itâ€™s not fast, easy money. If you have programming skills, itâ€™s a lot easier to get paid well by working as an employee slinging code than finding enough clients to make a living freelance writing.</p>

<p>On the flip side, youâ€™ll get paid to learn new concepts and help teach them to other people. Iâ€™ve gotten job inquiries, and other freelance writing offers simply as a result of being published on clientsâ€™ blogs.</p>

<p>Youâ€™ll need to be detail-oriented enough to write good content, but not so much that you canâ€™t finish an article and get it in on time. Time management is crucial. When youâ€™re freelance writing, youâ€™ll set your own deadlines, but nobody is going to be standing over you asking when youâ€™ll finish - you just wonâ€™t get paid until you do. Publishers prefer working with freelancers they can count on to get their work done on time and at a consistent quality.</p>

